@QiangCai thanks for working on this, with this feature, user can use dataframe as input to load carbondata files and without saving temporary CSV files. 
The only problem here is that it is still requiring 2 scan of the input dataframe, we probably should have another PR to explore the 1 scan approach.

@QiangCai @jackylk  I think this approach requires to execute dataframe twice. It is not recommendable to execute twice  as we don' t know the cost of execution of dataframe twice and it may end up with taking long time. And also caching dataframe is also not a good idea as we don't know the size of out put.  I think we can better keep the csv (compressed csv)staging solution until we find the single pass data loading solution.

@ravipesala can we keep it as an alternative to the current loading process? You are right about the data frame execution cost, however, I can still see some benefit:
1. no temporary CSV file is required, so that less disk space is required, if the user does not have enough disk space.
2. say, this data frame is from a hive table, ORC scan is much more efficient than compressed CSV scan due to better compression of ORC, and it also doesn't require the CSV data write cost, so data frame execution cost should be less in this case, which I think is typical use case nowadays
3. as we go forward, I think this is the first step toward non-kettle solution, we need to do this anyway in the future.

What is your idea? Do you think we should find a way to keep both approaches?

@jackylk @ravipesala 
If the output set is small and select query take a long time, maybe compressed Csv solution is better
If the output set is big, maybe load dataframe solution is better.

Now We can keep two solutions. And carbon user can choose a better solution for the special dataframe.

@QiangCai @jackylk @ravipesala  This is good feature and long waiting one. I also have concern about executing DF twice, before we figuring out the detail of one single pass data loading,  we actually could first introduce a version without global dictionary generation, fall back to local dictionary encoding or alternatively the table might already  have global dictionary in place (under metadata) or allowing user to supply global dictionary if it is generated somewhere else, so that this piece of work can still align with the ultimate single pass solution with global dictionary generation on the fly.  it looks to me eliminating the intermediate csv file is urgent hence has higher priority.
